The `\multirow` command in LaTeX is used to place multiple rows of content into a single cell of a table. The first argument is the number of rows to be occupied by the content, and the second argument is the content itself.

The `*` symbol in the first argument of `\multirow` indicates that the height of the cell should be automatically calculated based on the content. So, `\multirow{5}{*}{Content}` means that the content will occupy five rows, and the height of each row will be adjusted to fit the content.

Here's an example:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{multirow}

\begin{document}

\begin{table}
\centering
\begin{tabular}{|m{3cm}|m{3cm}|}
\hline
\multirow{5}{*}{Long content that spans five rows} & Normal content in the second column \\ \hline
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\end{document}
```

In this example, the content "Long content that spans five rows" will be displayed in five rows, with each row adjusted to fit the content. The second column will display the normal content as usual.

