To replace Google authentication with a reCAPTCHA in your web application, follow these steps:

1. Get your reCAPTCHA API keys:
   Go to the Google Cloud Console (https://console.cloud.google.com/) and sign in with your Google account. Create a new project or use an existing one. Enable the reCAPTCHA API for your project. Then, go to the "APIs & Services" > "Credentials" tab and create new reCAPTCHA keys. You'll need to create two keys: a site key and a secret key.

2. Update your HTML:
   In your HTML, replace the Google authentication script with the reCAPTCHA script. Add the following script tag to your HTML file:

   ```html
   <script src="https://www.google.com/recaptch/api.js" async defer></script>
   ```

3. Add reCAPTCHA to your form:
   Add the `data-sitekey` attribute to your form element and the `g-recaptcha` class to a hidden input element. Replace `YOUR_SITE_KEY` with the site key you obtained in step 1.

   ```html
   <form id="myForm">
     <!-- Your form fields here -->
     <div class="g-recaptcha" data-sitekey="YOUR_SITE_KEY"></div>
     <input type="hidden" name="g-recaptcha" id="g-recaptcha">
     <button type="submit">Submit</button>
   </form>
   ```

4. Update your JavaScript:
   Add the following JavaScript code to handle the reCAPTCHA verification when the form is submitted. Replace `YOUR_SECRET_KEY` with the secret key you obtained in step 1.

   ```javascript
   document.getElementById('myForm').addEventListener('submit', async (event) => {
     event.preventDefault();

     const response = await grecaptch.ready('g-recaptcha');
     const token = await response.execute();

     document.getElementById('g-recaptcha').value = token;

     // Send the form data with the reCAPTCHA token to your server
     const formData = new FormData(event.target);
     const response = await fetch('/submit', {
       method: 'POST',
       body: formData
     });

     if (response.ok) {
       // Handle successful submission
     } else {
       // Handle error
     }
   });
   ```

5. Update your server-side code:
   On the server-side, check if the reCAPTCHA token is valid by sending a request to the Google reCAPTCHA API with the secret key and the token. If the token is valid, process the form data as usual. If the token is invalid, return an error response.

   Here's a simple example in Node.js using Express:

   ```javascript
   const express = require('express');
   const axios = require('axios');

   const app = express();

   app.post('/submit', async (req, res) => {
     const secretKey = 'YOUR_SECRET_KEY';
     const token = req.body.g-recaptcha;

     try {
       const response = await axios.post('https://www.google.com/recaptcha/api/siteverify', null, {
         params: {
           secret: secretKey,
           response: token
         }
       });

       if (response.data.success) {
         // Process the form data
       } else {
         res.status(400).send('Invalid reCAPTCHA');
       }
     } catch (error) {
       res.status(500).send('Error');
     }
   });

   app.listen(3000, () => console.log('Server started on port 3000'));
   ```

Sure thing, homie. Dependency injection, or DI for short, is all about keepin' your code lean and mean. It's like when you send your boy to the corner store to get you a sandwich, but instead of havin' him make the sandwich himself, you send him with a pre-made one. That way, he ain't wastin' time and resources makin' the sandwich when he could be doin' other things for you.

In the context of C#, dependency injection is about separatin' the creation and management of objects from the code that uses them. Instead of havin' your code create and manage its own dependencies, you pass those dependencies in as arguments when you create the code. This way, you can keep your code focused on what it does best, and you can easily swap out dependencies or change their behavior without changin' the code itself.

So, instead of havin' your code like this:
```csharp
public class MyCode
{
    private MyDependency _dependency;

    public MyCode()
    {
        _dependency = new MyDependency();
    }

    public void DoSomething()
    {
        _dependency.DoSomethingElse();
        // other code here
    }
}
```
You can use dependency injection to make it look like this:
```csharp
public interface IMyDependency
{
    void DoSomethingElse();
}

public class MyCode
{
    private IMyDependency _dependency;

    public MyCode(IMyDependency dependency)
    {
        _dependency = dependency;
    }

    public void DoSomething()
    {
        _dependency.DoSomethingElse();
        // other code here
    }
}

public class MyDependency : IMyDependency
{
    // implementation here
}
```
Now, instead of havin' your code create its own dependency, you're passin' it in as an argument when you create the code. This way, you can easily swap out the dependency with a different implementation, or even inject a mock dependency for testin'. It's all about keepin' your code lean, mean, and flexible, homie.
